"And one who was at home in the district, for the pool can onlybe approached by the farm or by the estate, where strangers couldhardly wander.""Quite so.""Then comes our expedition of to-day. By an examination of theground I gained the trifling details which I gave to thatimbecile Lestrade, as to the personality of the criminal.""But how did you gain them?""You know my method. It is founded upon the observation oftrifles.""His height I know that you might roughly judge from the lengthof his stride. His boots, too, might be told from their traces.""Yes, they were peculiar boots.""But his lameness?""The impression of his right foot was always less distinct thanhis left. He put less weight upon it. Why? Because he limped--hewas lame.""But his left-handedness.""You were yourself struck by the nature of the injury as recorded